## Handling Complex Types and Generics in React

As your app grows, you’ll need advanced types like unions, intersections, and generics.

### Union Types

Use unions to allow multiple types for a prop:

```tsx
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';

interface StatusComponentProps {
  status: Status;
}

const StatusComponent: React.FC<StatusComponentProps> = ({ status }) => {
  if (status === 'loading') return <Spinner />;
  if (status === 'error') return <ErrorMessage />;
  return <SuccessMessage />;
};
```

### Intersection Types

Combine multiple types into one:

```tsx
interface BaseProps {
  className?: string;
}

interface ClickableProps {
  onClick: () => void;
}

type ButtonProps = BaseProps & ClickableProps;

const ClickableButton: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ className, onClick, children }) => {
  return (
    <button className={`btn ${className}`} onClick={onClick}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};
```

### Generics in Components

Generics allow components to accept dynamic types while maintaining type safety.

#### Example: Generic List Component

