# Chapter 5: Module 5: TypeScript with React for Type Safety

## Module 5: TypeScript with React for Type Safety

Type safety is one of the most powerful features TypeScript brings to React development. By integrating TypeScript with React, you can catch errors during development, improve code maintainability, and create more robust applications. This module will guide you through setting up TypeScript in a React project, typing React components, props, hooks, and handling complex types and generics.

---

## Setting Up TypeScript in a React Project

To use TypeScript with React, you’ll need to install the necessary dependencies and configure your project. Modern React projects created with Create React App (CRA) or Vite include TypeScript support out of the box.

### Using Create React App (CRA)

If you're starting a new project, run:

```bash
npx create-react-app my-app --template typescript
```

This sets up a React project with TypeScript already configured, including `tsconfig.json`, type definitions, and ESLint for TypeScript.

### Manual Setup (if not using CRA)

For existing projects or custom setups:

1. Install TypeScript and React type definitions:

```bash
npm install --save-dev typescript @types/react @types/react-dom
```

2. Create a `tsconfig.json` file with recommended settings:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "ES5",
    "lib": ["DOM", "DOM.Iterable", "ESNext"],
    "allowJs": true,
    "skipLibCheck": true,
    "esModuleInterop": true,
    "allowSyntheticDefaultImports": true,
    "strict": true,
    "forceConsistentCasingInFileNames": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,
    "module": "esnext",
    "moduleResolution": "node",
    "resolveJsonModule": true,
    "isolatedModules": true,
    "noEmit": true,
    "jsx": "react-jsx"
  },
  "include": ["src"]
}
```

This configuration ensures TypeScript understands JSX and React-specific types.

> ✅ Tip: Use `"strict": true` to enable all strict type-checking options for maximum type safety.

---

## Typing React Components and Props

TypeScript shines when typing React components and their props. Let’s explore how to define and enforce types for components.

### Functional Components with TypeScript

Define a functional component with typed props using an interface or type alias:

```tsx
import React from 'react';

interface ButtonProps {
  text: string;
  onClick: () => void;
  disabled?: boolean;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({
  text,
  onClick,
  disabled = false,
  variant = 'primary'
}) => {
  return (
    <button
      onClick={onClick}
      disabled={disabled}
      className={`btn btn-${variant}`}
    >
      {text}
    </button>
  );
};

export default Button;
```

> 🔍 Notice:
> - `React.FC<ButtonProps>` is a generic type from React that types the component function.
> - Optional props (like `disabled?` and `variant?`) are marked with `?`.
> - Default values are set in destructuring.

### Example: A Typed Product Card Component

Let’s build a product card that displays product information and accepts a product object as a prop.

```tsx
interface Product {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  price: number;
  inStock: boolean;
  rating: number;
  tags?: string[];
}

interface ProductCardProps {
  product: Product;
  onAddToCart: (productId: number) => void;
}

const ProductCard: React.FC<ProductCardProps> = ({ product, onAddToCart }) => {
  return (
    <div className="product-card">
      <h3>{product.name}</h3>
      <p>${product.price.toFixed(2)}</p>
      <p>Rating: {product.rating}/5</p>
      <button
        disabled={!product.inStock}
        onClick={() => onAddToCart(product.id)}
      >
        {product.inStock ? 'Add to Cart' : 'Out of Stock'}
      </button>
      {product.tags && (
        <div className="tags">
          {product.tags.map(tag => (
            <span key={tag} className="tag">{tag}</span>
          ))}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};
```

This component is fully typed:
- `Product` defines the structure of the product data.
- `ProductCardProps` types the component’s props.
- The component itself is typed as `React.FC<ProductCardProps>`.

> 💡 Best Practice: Define interfaces for data models separately and reuse them across components.

---

## Typing React Hooks

React hooks like `useState`, `useEffect`, and `useReducer` can also be typed to prevent runtime errors.

### Typing `useState`

```tsx
const [count, setCount] = useState<number>(0);
const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
const [filters, setFilters] = useState<{ sortBy: 'price' | 'name'; order: 'asc' | 'desc' }>({
  sortBy: 'price',
  order: 'asc'
});
```

### Typing `useEffect`

While `useEffect` itself doesn’t need explicit typing, you can type the dependencies array for better safety:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  // Fetch user data
}, [user?.id]); // Only re-run when user.id changes
```

### Typing `useReducer`

The `useReducer` hook benefits greatly from TypeScript. Define the state and action types:

```tsx
type UserState = {
  users: User[];
  loading: boolean;
  error: string | null;
};

type UserAction =
  | { type: 'FETCH_USERS_START' }
  | { type: 'FETCH_USERS_SUCCESS'; payload: User[] }
  | { type: 'FETCH_USERS_FAILURE'; payload: string };

const userReducer = (state: UserState, action: UserAction): UserState => {
  switch (action.type) {
    case 'FETCH_USERS_START':
      return { ...state, loading: true };
    case 'FETCH_USERS_SUCCESS':
      return { ...state, loading: false, users: action.payload };
    case 'FETCH_USERS_FAILURE':
      return { ...state, loading: false, error: action.payload };
    default:
      return state;
  }
};

const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(userReducer, {
  users: [],
  loading: false,
  error: null
});
```

This ensures that actions are validated at compile time.

---

## Handling Complex Types and Generics in React

As your app grows, you’ll need advanced types like unions, intersections, and generics.

### Union Types

Use unions to allow multiple types for a prop:

```tsx
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';

interface StatusComponentProps {
  status: Status;
}

const StatusComponent: React.FC<StatusComponentProps> = ({ status }) => {
  if (status === 'loading') return <Spinner />;
  if (status === 'error') return <ErrorMessage />;
  return <SuccessMessage />;
};
```

### Intersection Types

Combine multiple types into one:

```tsx
interface BaseProps {
  className?: string;
}

interface ClickableProps {
  onClick: () => void;
}

type ButtonProps = BaseProps & ClickableProps;

const ClickableButton: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ className, onClick, children }) => {
  return (
    <button className={`btn ${className}`} onClick={onClick}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};
```

### Generics in Components

Generics allow components to accept dynamic types while maintaining type safety.

#### Example: Generic List Component

```tsx
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

const List = <T extends {}>({ items, renderItem }: ListProps<T>) => {
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map((item, index) => (
        <li key={index}>{renderItem(item)}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
};

// Usage
interface Todo {
  id: number;
