### ## Monorepos with Turborepo and Nx

A **monorepo** (monolithic repository) is a single Git repository that contains multiple projects (apps, libraries, tools). Monorepos are ideal for scaling React applications because they:

- Simplify dependency management
- Enable code sharing across projects
- Support parallel builds and testing
- Encourage consistency in tooling and standards

Let’s look at two modern tools for managing monorepos: **Turborepo** and **Nx**.

---

#### Turborepo

[Turborepo](https://turbo.build/repo) is a high-performance build system for JavaScript/TypeScript monorepos. It uses **incremental builds** and **smart caching** to speed up development.

##### Example: Setting Up Turborepo

```bash
# Create a new Turborepo
npx create-turbo@latest
```

This scaffolds a monorepo with:

```
apps/
  web/          # React app
  docs/         # Documentation site
packages/
  shared-ui/    # Shared React components
  shared-utils/ # Shared utility functions
```

Turborepo uses a `turbo.json` configuration file to define tasks:

```json
// turbo.json
{
  "$schema": "https://turbo.build/schema.json",
  "pipeline": {
    "build": {
      "dependsOn": ["^build"],
      "outputs": ["dist/**"]
    },
    "lint": {
      "outputs": []
    },
    "dev": {
      "cache": false
    }
  }
}
```

Now, running `turbo build` will:

- Cache build outputs
- Run builds in parallel
- Skip unchanged packages if their dependencies haven’t changed

> 📌 **Real-world Example**: Vercel uses Turborepo to manage its massive monorepo, which includes Next.js, SvelteKit, and other frameworks. This allows them to build and test changes across all projects in seconds.

---

#### Nx

[Nx](https://nx.dev) is a powerful monorepo toolkit that goes beyond just builds. It includes:

- Dependency graph visualization
- Affected command (only rebuild/test what changed)
- First-class support for React, Next.js, and other frameworks
- Code generation (e.g., `nx g @nx/react:lib my-lib`)

##### Example: Setting Up Nx

```bash
# Install Nx globally
npm install -g nx

# Create a new Nx workspace
npx create-nx-workspace@latest my-monorepo
```

Choose the React preset, and Nx will scaffold a monorepo with:

```
apps/
  web/             # React app
libs/
  shared/ui/       # Shared React components
  shared/utils/    # Shared utilities
```

Nx uses a `project.json` or `package.json` to define tasks. For example:

```json
// libs/shared/ui/project.json
{
  "name": "shared-ui",
  "targets": {
    "build": {
      "executor": "@nx/webpack:webpack",
      "outputs": ["{options.outputPath}"]
    },
    "lint": {
      "executor": "@nx/linter:eslint"
    }
  }
}
```

Nx’s **affected commands** are a game-changer:

```bash
# Only lint, test, and build what changed since main
nx affected:lint
nx affected:test
nx affected:build
```

This makes CI pipelines faster and reduces feedback loops.

